# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1915-chicago-whales-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-chicago-federals-season] The **1914 Chicago Federals season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-chicago-federals-season] Chicago finished 87–67, good for 2nd place in the Federal League, just 1½ games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1914 Indianapolis Hoosiers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The Hoosiers won the inaugural Federal League championship, finishing 88–65, 1½ games ahead of the Chicago Federals.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The offensive star of the team was outfielder Benny Kauff, who led the league in batting average (.370), runs scored (120), and stolen bases (75).
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Future Hall of Famers Edd Roush and Bill McKechnie also saw significant playing time, and Indianapolis scored a league-high 762 runs.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Their rotation ace, Cy Falkenberg, went 25–16 with a 2.22 earned run average; he topped the circuit with 236 strikeouts.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] The **1915 Baltimore Terrapins season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] The Terrapins finished in 8th place in the Federal League, 40 games behind the Chicago Whales.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-baltimore-terrapins-season] After the season, both the team and the league folded.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The **1915 Boston Braves season** was the 45th season of the franchise.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The Braves finished second in the National League with a record of 83 wins and 69 losses, seven games behind the National League champion Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The 1915 season was notable for the opening of Braves Field on August 13, the last of the National League's "jewel box" stadiums to be built.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-braves-season] In the final game of the season, a 15–8 loss to the New York Giants, Joe Shannon made his final Major League appearance, and Red Shannon made his first Major League appearance.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-braves-season] The two were twins, marking the first of three times that twins played on the same team (along with Eddie and Johnny O'Brien and Jose and Ozzie Canseco).
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] The **1915 Boston Red Sox season** was the 15th season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 101 wins and 50 losses.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] The team then faced the National League (NL) champion Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series, which the Red Sox won in five games to capture the franchise's third World Series.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-boston-red-sox-season] While the Red Sox' home field was Fenway Park, their two home games of the World Series were played at Braves Field, due to its larger seating capacity.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-brooklyn-robins-season] The **1915 Brooklyn Robins season** improved enough to finish in third place, just 10 games behind the National League champion Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-brooklyn-robins-season] It was the teams first winning season since 1903 when they were still known as the Superbas.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The **1915 Brooklyn Tip-Tops season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The Tip-Tops finished in 7th place in the Federal League, 16 games behind the Chicago Whales.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The season was notable in that it featured one of the only known major-league professional baseball games of the modern era in which admission was free (June 28, 1914, vs. the Chicago Whales).
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-chicago-whales-season] The **1915 Chicago Whales season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-chicago-whales-season] After not having an official nickname in 1914, the team officially became the **Whales** for the 1915 season.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-chicago-whales-season] They finished the season with an 86–66 record, placing them in a statistical tie with the St.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-chicago-whales-season] Louis Terriers for first place in the Federal League.
[src:1915-chicago-whales-season/1915-chicago-whales-season] However, since the Whales had a slightly better winning percentage, they were declared the league champions.
